│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanTransforms.cpp"]], "thoughts": "### 1.      │
│ Understanding the Issue\n\nThe vectorizer is aborting due to an assertion       │
│ failure: `VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed`. This assertion is  │
│ a safeguard to ensure that the new VPlan-based cost model and the older,        │
│ \"legacy\" cost model either agree on the best vectorization factor (VF) or     │
│ that there's a good reason for their disagreement. The allowed reason for       │
│ disagreement is that the VPlan-based approach was able to perform extra         │
│ optimizations (`planContainsAdditionalSimplifications`) that the legacy model   │
│ doesn't account for, leading it to choose a better VF.\n\nIn this case, the     │
│ assertion is firing, which means:\n1. The VPlan cost model chose a different VF │
│ than the legacy cost model.\n2. The `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications`     │
│ check returned `false`, indicating that the VPlan for the new model's chosen VF │
│ doesn't seem to have any special optimizations that would justify the different │
│ decision.\n\nThis points to a discrepancy in how the two cost models evaluate   │
│ the profitability of vectorizing the loop.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s          │
│ Log\n\nThe `opt` log and backtrace confirm the crash location is inside         │
│ `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF` at `LoopVectorize.cpp:7364`. This is  │
│ the exact location of the assertion. The key is to understand *why* the two     │
│ cost models came to different conclusions for the provided reproducer.\n\nLet's │
│ examine the state at the crash point:\n- The legacy cost model, through         │
│ `selectVectorizationFactor()`, decided that vectorization is not profitable and │
│ returned a VF of 1 (i.e., don't vectorize).\n- The VPlan-based cost model,      │
│ however, determined that a VF of 2 is optimal.\n\nSince `1 != 2`, the assertion │
│ condition `BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width` is false. The vectorizer then    │
│ checks if the VPlan for VF=2 contains additional simplifications. It does not   │
│ find any, so the second part of the `||` is also false, and the program         │
│ aborts.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how    │
│ the two cost models handle a specific instruction pattern in the loop: the      │
│ `trunc` of a \"free\" induction variable.\n\nThe loop contains this phi         │
│ node:\n`%iv.conv = phi i32 [ %x.i32, %entry ], [ %3, %loop ]`\n\nAnd this       │
│ `trunc` instruction:\n`%3 = trunc i64 %iv.next to i32`\n\nHere, `%iv.next` is   │
│ derived from the main `i64` induction variable `%iv`. The `trunc` creates a     │
│ `i32` induction variable, `%iv.conv`. The key is that `%iv.conv` is a \"free\"  │
│ induction variable in this context. Because the target is RISC-V with the `+v`  │
│ (vector) extension, the `trunc` operation on the induction variable can often   │
│ be folded into the addressing modes of vector memory instructions, making it    │
│ effectively \"free\" (zero-cost).\n\nThe legacy cost model                      │
│ (`selectVectorizationFactor`) correctly identifies this `trunc` as a free       │
│ operation for the RISC-V target. It therefore calculates a low cost for the     │
│ loop, but still concludes that vectorization is not profitable, likely due to   │
│ the overhead of setting up the vector loop.\n\nThe VPlan-based cost model, on   │
│ the other hand, fails to recognize that this `trunc` is free. It models the     │
│ `trunc` as a `VPInstruction` that will be widened into a vector `trunc`         │
│ instruction, assigning it a non-zero cost. This extra cost is enough to tip the │
│ scales in its calculation, making it believe that vectorizing with VF=2 is      │
│ profitable (as it incorrectly assumes it is eliminating the cost of two `trunc` │
│ instructions in the scalar loop).\n\nThis discrepancy—the legacy model seeing a │
│ free `trunc` and the VPlan model seeing a costly one—is the root cause of the   │
│ disagreement. The VPlan model's cost assessment is inaccurate for this specific │
│ case.\n\nThe fix is to teach the VPlan infrastructure that a `trunc` of an      │
│ induction variable can be free. We can do this by adding a check in             │
│ `VPlanTransforms::optimizeForVFAndUF`. If a `VPInstruction` is a `trunc` and    │
│ its operand is a `VPWidenCanonicalIVRecipe` (which represents the main          │
│ induction variable), we can mark the `trunc` instruction as \"deleted,\"        │
│ effectively removing its cost from the VPlan's calculation.\n\n### 4. Proposed  │
│ Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix involves modifying                                     │
│ `VPlanTransforms::optimizeForVFAndUF` to recognize and eliminate the cost of    │
│ the free `trunc`.\n\n**File**:                                                  │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanTransforms.cpp`\n\n```cpp\n// Edit at line  │
│ 100\nfor (VPRecipeBase &Recipe : VPBB) {\n  if (auto *VPInst =                  │
│ dyn_cast<VPInstruction>(&Recipe)) {\n    if (VPInst->getOpcode() ==             │
│ Instruction::Trunc) {\n      auto *IV =\n                                       │
│ dyn_cast<VPWidenCanonicalIVRecipe>(VPInst->getOperand(0));\n      if (IV &&     │
│ IV->isCanonical()) {\n        VPInst->setDeleted();\n        continue;\n        │
│ }\n    }\n```\n\nThis change introduces a check within the recipe-optimization  │
│ loop. It looks for `VPInstruction`s that are `trunc` operations. If the operand │
│ of the `trunc` is the canonical induction variable, it marks the                │
│ `VPInstruction` as deleted. This prevents it from contributing to the cost      │
│ calculation, aligning the VPlan cost model's behavior with the legacy model for │
│ this pattern.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe assertion failure was caused by a     │
│ disagreement between the legacy and VPlan cost models on the cost of a `trunc`  │
│ instruction on an induction variable. The legacy model correctly identified it  │
│ as a zero-cost operation for the RISC-V vector target, while the VPlan model    │
│ did not. The proposed edit rectifies this by teaching the VPlan optimization    │
│ phase to identify and effectively ignore these \"free\" truncations. This will  │
│ align the cost models, resolve the assertion, and allow the vectorizer to make  │
│ a correct and consistent profitability decision."})                             │
